title: 2025 MountainTrue BioBlitz at Hickory Nut Gap Farm near Asheville, NC 6/21
description:
Each year, MountainTrue hosts a BioBlitz to record all the species we can find in a given area. We identify and catalog organisms using the online app iNaturalist. The BioBiltz this year will be on June 21st at Hickory Nut Gap Farm near Asheville, NC.
Volunteers will hike with experts in reptiles/amphibians, mammals, birds, plants, and mushrooms.
*Group sign-ups are taken at the event and are first come, first serve.  Group availability is subject to change.

We will meet at 12:30 pm to complete waivers and sign-up for groups. The BioBlitz will kick off at 1 pm and end at 5 pm. But the fun doesn’t stop there. We hope our volunteers will stick around for the barn dance at Hickory Nut Gap from 5 to 9 pm. All BioBlitz volunteers will receive free admission to the barn dance. 

Garage BBQ food truck will be on site where you can purchase dinner. MountainTrue will provide snacks.

Please bring: water, sunscreen, bug spray, notebook (if desired), sturdy close-toed shoes and any snacks, etc. that you may need.

**Kids aged 6 and up are welcome to join if they are accompanied by a parent/guardian for the duration of the trip.

The nation and our state are at a turning point, and YOU can be part of the movement shaping our democracy for the better. Get an inside look at how the California RCV Coalition is building momentum, raising awareness, and mobilizing communities to champion RCV statewide.  

**3️⃣ Find Out How You Can Make a Difference**  
Whether you're an experienced activist or just starting to explore RCV, there’s a role for you! Learn how you can contribute by:  
- Volunteering in your community or online  
- Donating to fuel the fight for fairer elections  

### **Who Should Attend?**  
This event is for anyone passionate about democracy, justice, and making every vote count. Whether you're a longtime supporter of RCV or curious about how it works and why it matters, you’ll walk away inspired and empowered to take action.  

**Together, we can create a more just and representative democracy in California. Don’t miss this chance to be part of history.**  

Let’s build a brighter future—starting with fairer elections. 🌟

title: Food Scraps Collection: Burbank Farmers Market
description:
As a volunteer, you’ll be right in the action, collecting food scraps from market-goers—the first step in a crucial process that turns waste into nutrient-rich compost. These scraps, gathered at local markets, are then processed at nearby green parks or gardens. Throughout your shift, you'll be guided by an experienced LA Compost staff member, who will act as your Compost Manager, offering insights and helping you share the benefits of composting with the public. The best part is that during your volunteer shift, you can take some time to shop at the market. Join us and be part of the composting movement that's transforming LA—one food scrap at a time!

#### ABOUT ACTIVITY:
As a volunteer, you’ll play a hands-on role in guiding market-goers through composting, ensuring their food scraps are clean of stickers, compostable, and ready to be turned into nutrient-rich compost. You’ll monitor for contamination, assist with tracking data, and serve as a friendly, welcoming host to our composting community. 

#### MORE INFO: 
* You'll be stationed at the LA Compost booth under a pop-up canopy within the farmers' market. There will also be seating available.
* You may be asked to assist with moving filled bins of material weighing 60+ pounds. We always offer team lifts; you will never be asked to lift bins if you prefer not to.
* No prior composting experience is needed; everyone is welcome!
* Bathrooms are available
* If you sign up, please show up! We rely on volunteers like you to achieve our mission.  
* We’ll follow up with details via email, so be sure to provide your best contact email when signing up.

#### AGE REQUIREMENT:
This volunteer activity is best suited for volunteers aged 16 and up. Minors under 16 should come accompanied by a parent or guardian unless other arrangements are made. Contact ashleigh@lacompost.org for more information.

#### IMPORTANT: VOLUNTEER WAIVER
Please make sure you have signed the volunteer waiver. 
Access the e-wavier at https://www.lacompost.org/waiver

address_lines: This event’s address is private. Sign up for more details
location.venue: This event’s address is private. Sign up for more details

description:
Join us for an impactful virtual event where we will write letters to our elected representatives, urging them to prioritize the issues that matter most to us and our communities. With the legislative session underway, it’s more important than ever to communicate directly with our lawmakers. Representatives need our voices to understand what is happening in our communities and make decisions that truly reflect our needs. The more people who get involved, the stronger our message will be! Not sure who your representatives are? No worries! We’ll help you find them.

Invite your friends to join us—together, we can create real change. Whether you're new to contacting your representatives or have written before, your participation is essential to shaping the future of our democracy.

Let’s stand up for democracy and take action during this important legislative session!


##### Please remember that all events hosted by the League of Women Voters of Houston are strictly nonpartisan. We ask that you please refrain from candidate and party specific conversations and wearing campaign merch from any active or past candidate.

title: Sing Songs of Resistance with The Audacity in Rockland
description:
Join this weekly Sing Out held by the new locally-organized creative protest group called [The Audacity](https://audacitycat.com). All those in opposition to the bigotry, corruption, and fascism being imposed by Donald Trump as his minions are welcome. We will gather at Chapman Park (Corner of Park and Main Streets, next to the Walgreens) every Saturday at Noon as long as Trump remains in the White House. We will sing songs of protest, resistance, freedom, and a better world. Teach a song you learned when you were young, learn a song from social movement veterans, and sing together in community. When we sing together, we tell each other that we are not alone, we provide community support and resilience, and together we weave a web that can hold down even a rabid, raging, lion.

![Join The Audacity in Public Square Protest Singing](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/675af046a62f855ee0072d1b/ee5d2c4b-7e47-4c86-8970-aa96a93f0f0e/JoinTheAudacityFacebookWeeklySingOut.png)

title: Lower Nob Hill Weekly Cleanup
description:
Lower Nob Hill is a vibrant community, with diverse small businesses and a lively urban spirit. We take pride in our neighborhood and want it to shine! Since July 2021, dedicated volunteers have come together each Sunday morning to clean our sidewalks, build connections, and take pride in improving our shared space.

Join us and be part of the difference! Volunteers meet at Another Cafe (1191 Pine St at Leavenworth St, meet on the Leavenworth side) at 9:45 AM to receive supplies, a cleanup route, a partner, and instructions. Teams head out promptly at 10:00 AM to pick up trash, returning by 11:00 AM. Afterwards, stick around for free food, refreshments, and a chance to connect with fellow volunteers.

Lower Nob Hill Weekly Cleanup is made possible by our incredible volunteers, with funding from the Civic Joy Fund and support from Refuse Refuse. Supplies are provided by SF Public Works.

Your help makes all the difference—come join us in keeping Lower Nob Hill beautiful!

title: The Tapestry of Black Voices Awards
description:
We are excited to announce that Conversations in Color, a Black-led nonprofit organization, will be hosting the upcoming "Tapestry of Black Voices Awards."  

At Conversations in Color, we are deeply committed to nurturing uplifting conversations and fostering stronger community connections for Black voices. Through the “Tapestry of Black Voices Awards,” we aim to honor and celebrate these voices within our local communities.

We will begin accepting entries in May and on Juneteenth 2025, we will host a virtual awards show that will serve as a platform to showcase the remarkable interwoven voices of the Black community across various cities. 

In our endeavor to make the “Tapestry of Black Voices Awards” a resounding success, we invite all Black community stakeholders to join us in this important initiative. There are several ways in which you can contribute and make a meaningful impact:

1. Consider Submitting an Entry: If you or someone you know would like to showcase their unique voice or story with a larger audience, we encourage you to submit an entry. Simply create a short video that highlights a conversation among local community members. There are seven categories ranging from HBCU/BSU conversations, community issues, Black-Owned spotlights and more! *Detailed submission guidelines will be released in March 2025. https://2025awards.conversationsincolor.org/categories/

2. Sponsor the Award Show: By becoming a sponsor of the award show, you will not only be aligning your brand with a worthy cause, but you will also have the opportunity to reach a nationwide audience and demonstrate your commitment to uplifting Black voices. We have created various sponsorship packages to accommodate different levels of involvement, allowing businesses of all sizes to make a meaningful impact. https://2025awards.conversationsincolor.org/sponsorship/

3. Share the Opportunity: If you are unable to submit an entry or sponsor the award show, you can still play a crucial role by sharing this opportunity with individuals or organizations who might be interested. By spreading the word, you help us reach a wider audience and create more opportunities for Black voices to be celebrated and recognized. https://2025awards.conversationsincolor.org/welcome/

Every contribution, whether big or small, will help us create a meaningful impact in our communities.

title: Sister District SF: 2025 Monthly Citywide Zooms
description:
Join our Sister District SF monthly meeting to connect virtually as volunteers and neighbors, share news, and learn about the importance of state legislatures and opportunities to flip states from red to blue. 

You are welcome to join any of our monthly meetings, whichever is most convenient for you! 

We host events on **Zoom the first Tuesday** of each month; in-person **Happy Hours on the first Thursdays** of even-numbered months; in-person **Coffee Hours on first Thursdays** of odd-numbered months (locations vary); or in-person **Postcard events** on third Sundays or Mondays.

Last year, Sister District Project flipped critical seats in the North Carolina House and the Wisconsin Senate, breaking GOP supermajorities. In Pennsylvania, we defended our hard-fought Democratic majority in the House, and in Minnesota, we preserved Democratic control in a pivotal special election. Altogether, we endorsed 53 candidates in 9 states and won 31 races!

In 2023, SDP helped to flip Virginia's House of Delegates blue, while also keeping a blue hold the State Senate, ensuring that 35 million women in the south didn't lose vital healthcare access from the ONLY southern state without an abortion ban.
 
In 2022, SDP supported 18 state legislative races in battleground states and ALL of our candidates won—including in Arizona and Nevada, where the candidates Sister District SF supported directly were running (each chapter gets paired with two or more races each year).

Since 2016, we've been building enduring progressive power in the states to improve people's lives, including by supporting community-based organizations led by people of color on the ground, like [New Virginia Majority](https://secure.actblue.com/donate/sd016-va-nvmef-sf), who do critical grassroots work year round.

To learn more about Sister District Project's 2025 - 2026 strategy, visit [SisterDistrict.com] (https://sisterdistrict.com/strategy).
